{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is an optimization task where we need to maximize the sum of board entries by placing 3x3 stamps. Since the board is small (9x9) and the number of stamps is limited, this can be approached via a greedy strategy or a local search/hill climbing algorithm.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "greedy_strategy_developer",
      "instructions": "Develop a Python script that implements a greedy algorithm to solve the problem. The algorithm should: 1. Read the input N, M, K, the initial board, and the M stamps. 2. Iteratively select the stamp and position (i, j) that provides the maximum increase to the total sum of the board entries when added modulo 998244353. 3. Ensure that the placement (i, j) allows the 3x3 stamp to stay within the 9x9 board boundaries. 4. Stop when no more placements can increase the sum or when K placements are reached. 5. Output the number of placements L and then each placement as m i j."
    },
    {
      "label": "refinement_optimizer",
      "instructions": "Propose a local search or hill-climbing refinement for the greedy solution. Specifically, suggest how to take an existing set of placements and attempt to swap a placement for a different stamp or position, or add/remove a placement, to see if the total sum of the board (calculated modulo 998244353) increases. Provide the logic for calculating the delta in the total sum efficiently."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the greedy baseline script with the local search logic to create a robust main.py. The final solution should first run the greedy pass to get a strong starting point, then attempt a limited number of local search iterations to improve the score, ensuring all constraints (K <= 81, 3x3 bounds, modulo arithmetic) are strictly respected."
}

